# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carbon-monoxide-detector
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] An **alarm device** is a mechanism that gives an audible, visual, combination, or other kind of alarm signal to alert someone to a problem or condition that requires urgent attention.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] The word *alarm* comes from the Old French *a l'arme* meaning "to the arms", or "to the weapons", telling armed men to pick up their weapons and get ready for action because an enemy may have suddenly appeared.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] The word *alarum* is an archaic form of *alarm*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] It was sometimes used as a call to arms in the stage directions of Elizabethan dramas.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] The term comes from the Italian *all'armi* and appears 89 times in Shakespeare's First Folio.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Often explained as the off-stage sounds of conflict or disturbance, recent research suggests a bell or drum may have been used to rouse soldiers from sleep.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Early alarm devices were often bells, drums, other musical instruments, or any items which made unusual loud noises that attracted the attention of the surrounding population.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Whistles were used by police in the 19th century.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Steam whistles have been used on locomotives, ships, and in factories as alarm devices.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] With the advent of electricity, a variety of other alerting devices have been invented, such as buzzers, klaxons, sirens, horns, flashing and coloured lights, and other all-purpose alarms.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Alarm devices can be fitted to buildings as well as vehicles.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Many buildings are fitted with fire alarms, ranging from a self-contained domestic smoke detector to a sophisticated alarm system that can operate building fire fighting systems automatically to extinguish fires with water or inert gases.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Many industries have developed standards for alarm devices, and the colours red, blue and amber are generally recognized as alarm device-related colours, with flashing lights often indicating urgent conditions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Human reactions to an alarm will often depend on upbringing, psychological training, or the behavior of others in the environment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Consequently, the ability to test an alarm and hold regular drills to practice an appropriate response may be provided as part of an alarm system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Alarm devices that are intended to cause the evacuation of an occupied building, such as fire alarms, may be deliberately designed to make remaining in the space difficult or even painful in order to encourage occupants to leave.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Some alarms may startle and cause a fight-or-flight response in humans; a person under this mindset will panic and either flee the perceived danger or attempt to eliminate it, often ignoring rational thought in either case.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] A person in such a state can be characterized as "alarmed".
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] With any kind of alarm, people must balance between the danger of false alarms (called "false positives") — the signal going off in the absence of a problem — or an alarm failing to signal an actual problem (called a "false negative").
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] False alarms can waste resources expensively and can even be dangerous.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] For example, false alarms of a fire can waste firefighter manpower, making them unavailable for a real fire, and risk injury to firefighters and others as the fire engines race to the alleged fire's location.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] In addition, false alarms may acclimatise people to ignore alarm signals, and thus possibly to ignore an actual emergency: Aesop's fable of *The Boy Who Cried Wolf* exemplifies this problem.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] A false alarm is one of the most significant issues with conventional alarm systems.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] They can be triggered for several reasons, such as the movement of pets, typing in the wrong security codes, or loud sounds from windows or doors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] In the case of fire alarms, aerosol sprays, smoking, or burning food can all lead to a false alarm.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] Many avoid the risk of false alarms by ensuring their alarms are secured in an appropriate location, such as placing a smoke detector or fire alarm away from the kitchen where smoke from burned food or large quantities of steam which may trigger a false alarm are common occurrences.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alarm-device] In the case of a security alarm, an additional monitoring station which assesses whether there is a legitimate need for help can reduce false alarms.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta's economy is advanced, open, market-based, and characterized by a highly educated workforce, strong institutions and property rights, and sophisticated financial markets.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The service sector employs 80% of Albertans, in fields like healthcare, education, professional services, retail, tourism and financial services.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The industrial base includes manufacturing, construction, and agriculture (10%, 5%, and 2% of employment respectively), while the knowledge economy includes about 3000 tech companies employing an estimated 60,000 people, mainly in Calgary and Edmonton.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The energy sector employs 5% of Albertans but significantly impacts exports and GDP.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta's exports, primarily US-bound, consist of 70% oil and gas, 13% food products, and 12% industrial products.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Oil and gas are culturally influential, having shaped politics, generated "striking it rich" narratives, and created boom-and-bust cycles.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In 2023, Alberta's output was $350 billion, 15% of Canada's GDP.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Until the 1930s, Alberta's political landscape consisted of two major parties: the centre-left Liberals and the agrarian United Farmers of Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Today, Alberta is generally perceived as a conservative province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The right-wing Social Credit Party held office continually from 1935 to 1971 before the centre-right Progressive Conservatives held office continually from 1971 to 2015, the latter being the longest unbroken run in government at the provincial or federal level in Canadian history.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The United Conservative Party has held office since 2019.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Since before it became part of Canada, Alberta has been home to several First Nations, such as Plains Indians and Woodland Cree.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] It was historically also a territory used by fur traders of the rival companies Hudson's Bay Company and North West Company.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The Dominion of Canada bought the lands that would become Alberta as part of the NWT in 1870.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] From the late 1800s to the early 1900s, many immigrants arrived in an effort to prevent the prairies from being annexed by the United States.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Growing wheat and cattle ranching became very profitable during this period.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In 1905, the Alberta Act was passed, creating the province of Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Massive oil reserves were discovered in 1947.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The exploitation of oil sands began in 1967.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta is renowned for its natural beauty and is home to important nature reserves.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] It is also well known as a rich source of fossils.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] It is home to six UNESCO-designated World Heritage Sites: the Canadian Rocky Mountain Parks, Dinosaur Provincial Park, Head-Smashed-In Buffalo Jump, Waterton-Glacier International Peace Park, Wood Buffalo National Park and Writing-on-Stone Provincial Park.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Other popular sites include Banff National Park, Elk Island National Park, Jasper National Park, Waterton Lakes National Park, and Drumheller.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta was named after Princess Louise Caroline Alberta (1848–1939), the fourth daughter of Queen Victoria.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Princess Louise was the wife of John Campbell, Marquess of Lorne, Governor General of Canada (1878–83).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Lake Louise and Mount Alberta were also named in her honour.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The name "Alberta" is a feminine Latinized form of Albert, the name of Princess Louise's father, the Prince Consort (cf.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Medieval Latin: *Albertus*, masculine) and its Germanic cognates, ultimately derived from the Proto-Germanic language **Aþalaberhtaz* (compound of "noble" + "bright/famous").
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta, with an area of 661,848 km2 (255,541 sq mi), is the fourth-largest province after Quebec, Ontario, and British Columbia.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta's southern border is the 49th parallel north, which separates it from the U.S. state of Montana.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The 60th parallel north divides Alberta from the Northwest Territories.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The province extends 1,223 kilometres (760 mi) north to south and 660 km (410 mi) east to west at its maximum width.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Its highest point is 3,747 metres (12,293 ft) at the summit of Mount Columbia in the Rocky Mountains along the southwest border while its lowest point is 152 m (499 ft) on the Slave River in Wood Buffalo National Park in the northeast.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] With the exception of the semi-arid climate of the steppe in the south-eastern section, the province has adequate water resources.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] There are numerous rivers and lakes in Alberta used for swimming, fishing and a range of water sports.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] There are three large lakes, Lake Claire (1,436 km2 [554 sq mi]) in Wood Buffalo National Park, Lesser Slave Lake (1,168 km2 or 451 sq mi), and Lake Athabasca (7,898 km2 or 3,049 sq mi), which lies in both Alberta and Saskatchewan.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The longest river in the province is the Athabasca River, which travels 1,538 km (956 mi) from the Columbia Icefield in the Rocky Mountains to Lake Athabasca.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The largest river is the Peace River with an average flow of 2,100 cubic metres per second (74,000 cu ft/s).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The Peace River originates in the Rocky Mountains of northern British Columbia and flows through northern Alberta and into the Slave River, a tributary of the Mackenzie River.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta's capital city, Edmonton, is located roughly at the geographic centre of the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] It is the most northerly major city in Canada and serves as a gateway and hub for resource development in northern Canada.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] With its proximity to Canada's largest oil fields, the region has most of western Canada's oil refinery capacity.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Calgary is about 280 km (170 mi) south of Edmonton and 240 km (150 mi) north of Montana by highway, surrounded by extensive ranching country.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Almost 75% of the province's population lives in the Calgary–Edmonton Corridor.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The land grant policy to the railways served as a means to populate the province in its early years.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Most of the northern half of the province is boreal forest, while the Rocky Mountains along the southwestern boundary are largely temperate coniferous forests of the Alberta Mountain forests and Alberta–British Columbia foothills forests.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The southern quarter of the province is prairie, ranging from shortgrass prairie in the southeastern corner to mixed grass prairie in an arc to the west and north of it.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The central aspen parkland region extending in a broad arc between the prairies and the forests, from Calgary, north to Edmonton, and then east to Lloydminster, contains the most fertile soil in the province and most of the population.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Much of the unforested part of Alberta is given over either to grain farming or cattle ranching, with mixed farming more common in the north and centre, while ranching and irrigated agriculture predominate in the south.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The Alberta badlands are in southeastern Alberta, where the Red Deer River crosses the flat prairie and farmland, and features deep canyons and striking landforms.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Dinosaur Provincial Park, near Brooks, showcases the badlands terrain, desert flora, and remnants from Alberta's past when dinosaurs roamed the then lush landscape.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta extends for over 1,200 km (750 mi) from north to south; its climate, therefore, varies considerably.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Average high temperatures in January range from 0 °C (32 °F) in the southwest to −24 °C (−11 °F) in the far north.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The northerly location and isolation from the weather systems of the Pacific Ocean cause Alberta to have a dry climate with little moderation from the ocean.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Annual precipitation ranges from 300 millimetres (12 in) in the southeast to 450 mm (18 in) in the north, except in the foothills of the Rocky Mountains where total precipitation including snowfall can reach 600 mm (24 in) annually.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Northern Alberta is mostly covered by boreal forest and has a subarctic climate.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The agricultural area of southern Alberta has a semi-arid steppe climate because the annual precipitation is less than the water that evaporates or is used by plants.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The southeastern corner of Alberta, part of the Palliser Triangle, experiences greater summer heat and lower rainfall than the rest of the province, and as a result, suffers frequent crop yield problems and occasional severe droughts.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Western Alberta is protected by the mountains and enjoys the mild temperatures brought by winter Chinook winds.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Central and parts of northwestern Alberta in the Peace River region are largely aspen parkland, a biome transitional between prairie to the south and boreal forest to the north.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta has a humid continental climate with warm summers and cold winters.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The province is open to cold Arctic weather systems from the north, which often produce cold winter conditions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] As the fronts between the air masses shift north and south across Alberta, the temperature can change rapidly.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Arctic air masses in the winter produce extreme minimum temperatures varying from −54 °C (−65 °F) in northern Alberta to −46 °C (−51 °F) in southern Alberta, although temperatures at these extremes are rare.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In the summer, continental air masses have produced record maximum temperatures from 32 °C (90 °F) in the mountains to over 40 °C (104 °F) in southeastern Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Annual bright sunshine totals range between 1,900 up to just under 2,600 hours per year.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Northern Alberta gets about 18 hours of daylight in the summer.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The average daytime temperatures range from around 21 °C (70 °F) in the Rocky Mountain valleys and far north, up to around 28 °C (82 °F) in the dry prairie of the southeast.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The northern and western parts of the province experience higher rainfall and lower evaporation rates caused by cooler summer temperatures.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The south and east-central portions are prone to drought-like conditions sometimes persisting for several years, although even these areas can receive heavy precipitation, sometimes resulting in flooding.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In the winter, the Alberta clipper, a type of intense, fast-moving winter storm that generally forms over or near the province and, pushed with great speed by the continental polar jetstream, descends over the rest of southern Canada and the northern tier of the United States.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In southwestern Alberta, the cold winters are frequently interrupted by warm, dry Chinook winds blowing from the mountains, which can propel temperatures upward from frigid conditions to well above the freezing point in a very short period.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] During one Chinook recorded at Pincher Creek, temperatures soared from −19 to 22 °C (−2 to 72 °F) in just one hour.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The region around Lethbridge has the most Chinooks, averaging 30 to 35 Chinook days per year.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Calgary has a 56% chance of a white Christmas, while Edmonton has an 86% chance.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] After Saskatchewan, Alberta experiences the most tornadoes in Canada with an average of 15 verified per year.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Thunderstorms, some of them severe, are frequent in the summer, especially in central and southern Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The region surrounding the Calgary–Edmonton Corridor is notable for having the highest frequency of hail in Canada, which is caused by orographic lifting from the nearby Rocky Mountains, enhancing the updraft/downdraft cycle necessary for the formation of hail.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In central and northern Alberta the arrival of spring is marked by the early flowering of the prairie crocus (*Pulsatilla nuttalliana*) *anemone*; this member of the buttercup family has been recorded flowering as early as March, though April is the usual month for the general population.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Other prairie flora known to flower early are the golden bean (*Thermopsis rhombifolia*) and wild rose (*Rosa acicularis*).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Members of the sunflower (*Helianthus*) family blossom on the prairie in the summer months between July and September.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The southern and east central parts of Alberta are covered by short prairie grass, which dries up as summer lengthens, to be replaced by hardy perennials such as the prairie coneflower (*Ratibida*), fleabane, and sage (*Artemisia*).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Both yellow and white sweet clover (*Melilotus*) can be found throughout the southern and central areas of the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The trees in the parkland region of the province grow in clumps and belts on the hillsides.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] These are largely deciduous, typically aspen, poplar, and willow.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Many species of willow and other shrubs grow in virtually any terrain.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] North of the North Saskatchewan River, evergreen forests prevail for thousands of square kilometres.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Aspen poplar, balsam poplar (*Populus balsamifera*) or in some parts cottonwood (*Populus deltoides*), and paper birch (*Betula papyrifera*) are the primary large deciduous species.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Conifers include jack pine (*Pinus banksiana*), Rocky Mountain pine, lodgepole pine (*Pinus contorta*), both white and black spruce, and the deciduous conifer tamarack (*Larix laricina*).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The four climatic regions (alpine, boreal forest, parkland, and prairie) of Alberta are home to many different species of animals.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The south and central prairie was the homeland of the American bison, also known as buffalo, with its grasses providing pasture and breeding ground for millions of buffalo.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The buffalo population was decimated during early settlement, but since then, buffalo have made a comeback, living on farms and in parks all over Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Herbivores are found throughout the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Moose, mule deer, elk, and white-tailed deer are found in the wooded regions, and pronghorn can be found in the prairies of southern Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Bighorn sheep and mountain goats live in the Rocky Mountains.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Rabbits, porcupines, skunks, squirrels, and many species of rodents and reptiles live in every corner of the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta is home to only one venomous snake species, the prairie rattlesnake.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta is home to many large carnivores such as wolves, grizzly bears, black bears, and mountain lions, which are found in the mountains and wooded regions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Smaller carnivores of the canine and feline families include coyotes, red foxes, Canada lynx, and bobcats.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Wolverines can also be found in the northwestern areas of the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Central and northern Alberta and the region farther north are the nesting ground of many migratory birds.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Vast numbers of ducks, geese, swans and pelicans arrive in Alberta every spring and nest on or near one of the hundreds of small lakes that dot northern Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Eagles, hawks, owls, and crows are plentiful, and a huge variety of smaller seed and insect-eating birds can be found.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta, like other temperate regions, is home to mosquitoes, flies, wasps, and bees.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Rivers and lakes are populated with pike, walleye, whitefish, rainbow, speckled, brown trout, and sturgeon.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Native to the province, the bull trout, is the provincial fish and an official symbol of Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Turtles are found in some water bodies in the southern part of the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Frogs and salamanders are a few of the amphibians that make their homes in Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta is the only province in Canada—as well as one of the few places in the world—that is free from Norwegian rats.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Since the early 1950s, the Government of Alberta has operated a rat-control program, which has been so successful that only isolated instances of wild rat sightings are reported, usually of rats arriving in the province aboard trucks or by rail.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In 2006, Alberta Agriculture reported zero findings of wild rats; the only rat interceptions have been domesticated rats that have been seized from their owners.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] It is illegal for individual Albertans to own or keep Norwegian rats of any description; the animals can only be kept in the province by zoos, universities and colleges, and recognized research institutions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In 2009, several rats were found and captured, in small pockets in southern Alberta, putting Alberta's rat-free status in jeopardy.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] A colony of rats was subsequently found in a landfill near Medicine Hat in 2012 and again in 2014.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta has one of the greatest diversities and abundances of Late Cretaceous dinosaur fossils worldwide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Taxa are represented by complete fossil skeletons, isolated material, microvertebrate remains, and even mass graves.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] At least 38 dinosaur type specimens were collected in the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The Foremost Formation, Oldman Formation and Dinosaur Park Formations collectively compose the Judith River Group and are the most thoroughly studied dinosaur-bearing strata in Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Dinosaur-bearing strata are distributed widely throughout Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The Dinosaur Provincial Park area contains outcrops of the Dinosaur Park Formation and Oldman Formation.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In Alberta's central and southern regions are intermittent Scollard Formation outcrops.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In the Drumheller Valley and Edmonton regions there are exposed Horseshoe Canyon facies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Other formations have been recorded as well, like the Milk River and Foremost Formations.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The latter two have a lower diversity of documented dinosaurs, primarily due to their lower total fossil quantity and neglect from collectors who are hindered by the isolation and scarcity of exposed outcrops.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Their dinosaur fossils are primarily teeth recovered from microvertebrate fossil sites.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Additional geologic formations that have produced only a few fossils are the Belly River Group and St.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Mary River Formations of the southwest and the northwestern Wapiti Formation, which contains two *Pachyrhinosaurus* bone beds.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The Bearpaw Formation represents strata deposited during a marine transgression.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Dinosaurs are known from this formation, but represent specimens washed out to sea or reworked from older sediments.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Paleo-Indians arrived in what is now Alberta at least 10,000 years ago, toward the end of the last ice age.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] They are thought to have migrated from Siberia to Alaska on a land bridge across the Bering Strait and then possibly moved south along the east side of the Rocky Mountains through Alberta, settling along the way or moving on to settle other parts of the Americas.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Others may have travelled south along the west coast and then moved inland.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The first Europeans to visit Alberta were French Canadian fur traders in the early 18th century.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The first British subject to visit Alberta was Anthony Henday, in 1754.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] French Canadians integrated with local First Nations creating the Metis nation, with elements across the Prairies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] French was the predominant European language in Alberta and was used in some early fur trading forts in the region, such as the first Fort Edmonton (in present-day Fort Saskatchewan), operated by the Hudson's Bay Company (HBC).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] After the British arrival in Canada, approximately half of Alberta's current territory, south of the Athabasca River drainage, became part of Rupert's Land, which consisted of all land drained by rivers flowing into Hudson Bay.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] This area was granted by King Charles II of England to the Hudson's Bay Company in 1670, and rival fur trading companies were not allowed to trade in it.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The Athabasca River and the rivers north of it were not in HBC territory, because they drained into the Arctic Ocean instead of Hudson Bay.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The north part of Alberta was a prime habitat for fur-bearing animals and was targeted by the HBC and other fur trading companies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The first European explorer of the Athabasca region was fur trader Peter Pond, who learned of the Methye Portage, a convenient route to travel from rivers in the Hudson Bay watershed to rivers north of Rupert's Land.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] He and other Canadian fur traders formed the North West Company (NWC) of Montreal in 1779, to compete with the HBC.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The NWC built posts at many points across the northern part of Alberta territory.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Peter Pond built Fort Athabasca on Lac la Biche in 1778.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Roderick Mackenzie built Fort Chipewyan on Lake Athabasca ten years later in 1788.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] His cousin, Sir Alexander Mackenzie, followed the North Saskatchewan River to its northernmost point near Edmonton, then trekked on foot to the Athabasca River, which he followed downstream to Lake Athabasca.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] It was there he discovered the mighty outflow river that bears his name – the Mackenzie River – which he followed to its outlet in the Arctic Ocean.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Returning to Lake Athabasca, he followed the Peace River upstream and crossed the Rockies, eventually reaching the Pacific Ocean, and so he became the first European to cross the North American continent north of Mexico.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The extreme southernmost portion of Alberta was part of the French (and Spanish) territory of Louisiana, which was sold to the United States in 1803.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In the Treaty of 1818, the portion of the Louisiana territory north of the Forty-Ninth Parallel was ceded to the United Kingdom.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The area was grouped with Rupert's Land to make the North-Western Territory.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Fur trade expanded in the north, but there was intense friction and competition between the rival HBC and NWC.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In 1821 the British government forced them to merge to stop the hostilities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] After amalgamation, the Hudson's Bay Company dominated the economy of Alberta until 1870, when HBC control of Rupert's Land was ended and the territory was transferred to the newly federated Canada.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Southern Alberta, Northern Alberta, other parts of the Northland and Rupert's land became Canada's North-West Territories.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] First Nations and representatives of the Crown negotiated the Numbered Treaties, in which the Crown gained title to the land that would later become Alberta, and the Crown committed to the ongoing support of the First Nations and guaranteed their hunting and fishing rights.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The most significant treaties for Alberta are Treaty 6 (1876), Treaty 7 (1877) and Treaty 8 (1899).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The District of Alberta was created as part of the North-West Territories on 8 May 1882.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] As settlement increased, local representatives to the North-West Legislative Assembly and the House of Commons were elected, and senators appointed, to represent Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] After a long campaign for autonomy, on 1 September 1905, the District of Alberta was enlarged and given provincial status, with the election of a Liberal majority with Alexander Cameron Rutherford as the first premier.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] At first the economy was very active, then around 1912, Alberta suffered a recession.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The First World War presented special challenges to the new province as an extraordinary number of working-age men volunteered for active service, leaving relatively few workers to maintain services and production.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Over 50% of Alberta's doctors volunteered for service overseas.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In 1918 Albertans experienced the 1918 flu epidemic.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta voters sought innovation, electing a Farmers government in 1921, then the world's first Social Credit government in 1935.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta's economy stayed sluggish, especially during the Depression.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] But discovery of oil at Leduc in 1946 opened a new era of prosperity and wealth for the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] On June 21, 2013, during the 2013 Alberta floods Alberta experienced heavy rainfall that triggered catastrophic flooding throughout much of the southern half of the province along the Bow, Elbow, Highwood and Oldman rivers and tributaries.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] A dozen municipalities in Southern Alberta declared local states of emergency on June 21 as water levels rose and numerous communities were placed under evacuation orders.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In 2016, the Fort McMurray wildfire resulted in the largest fire evacuation of residents in Alberta's history, as more than 80,000 people were ordered to evacuate.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Like the rest of the world, Alberta was affected by the COVID-19 pandemic starting in 2020.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The last restrictions were lifted in 2022.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Statistics Canada estimated the province to have a population of 4,931,601 in Q4 of 2024.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Since 2000, Alberta's population has experienced a relatively high rate of growth, mainly because of its burgeoning economy.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Between 2003 and 2004, the province had high birthrates (on par with some larger provinces such as British Columbia), relatively high immigration, and a high rate of interprovincial migration compared to other provinces.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In 2016, Alberta continued to have the youngest population among the provinces with a median age of 36.7 years, compared with the national median of 41.2 years.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Also in 2016, Alberta had the smallest proportion of seniors (12.3%) among the provinces and one of the highest population shares of children (19.2%), further contributing to Alberta's young and growing population.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] About 81% of the population lives in urban areas and only about 19% in rural areas.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The Calgary–Edmonton Corridor is the most urbanized area in the province and is one of the most densely populated areas of Canada.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Many of Alberta's cities and towns have experienced very high rates of growth in recent history.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Additionally, as per the 2016 census, 1,769,500 residents hold a postsecondary certificate, diploma or degree, 895,885 residents have obtained a secondary (high) school diploma or equivalency certificate, and 540,665 residents do not have any certificate, diploma or degree.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The question on knowledge of languages allows for multiple responses.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] As of the 2016 census, English is the most common mother tongue, with 2,991,485 native speakers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] This is followed by Tagalog, with 99,035 speakers, German, with 80,050 speakers, French, with 72,150 native speakers, and Punjabi, with 68,695 speakers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The 2006 census found that English, with 2,576,670 native speakers, was the most common mother tongue of Albertans, representing 79.99% of the population.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The next most common mother tongues were Chinese with 97,275 native speakers (3.02%), followed by German with 84,505 native speakers (2.62%) and French with 61,225 (1.90%).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The most common aboriginal language is Cree 17,215 (0.53%).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] According to Statistics Canada, Alberta is home to the second-highest proportion (2%) of Francophones in western Canada (after Manitoba).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Despite this, relatively few Albertans claim French as their mother tongue.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Many of Alberta's French-speaking residents live in the central and northwestern regions of the province, after migration from other areas of Canada or descending from Métis.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta has considerable ethnic diversity.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In line with the rest of Canada, many Albertans are descended from immigrants of Western European nations, notably England, Scotland, Ireland, Wales and France, but large numbers later came from other regions of Europe, notably Germany, Ukraine and Scandinavia.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] More recently, Africans, Asians and South Americans in larger numbers have also contributed to Alberta's ethnic origins.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Many Alberta families today can trace their ethnicity in many directions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Amongst those of British heritage, the Scots have had a particularly strong influence on place-names.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Many cities and towns have names of Scottish origins, such as Calgary, Airdrie, Canmore, and Banff.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Both Edmonton and Calgary have historic Chinatowns, and Calgary has Canada's third-largest Chinese community.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The Chinese presence began with workers employed in the building of the Canadian Pacific Railway in the 1880s.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] In 2021, 27.8% of the population consisted of visible minorities and 6.8% of the population was Indigenous, mostly of First Nations and Métis descent.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] A small number of Inuit live in the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] The Indigenous population has been growing at a faster rate than the population of Alberta as a whole.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Some of this increase is due to Albertans who are only now embracing their Metis lineage.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] As of the 2011 National Household Survey, the largest religious group was Roman Catholic, representing 24.3% of the population.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta had the second-highest percentage of non-religious residents among the provinces (after British Columbia) at 31.6% of the population.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Of the remainder, 7.5% of the population identified themselves as belonging to the United Church of Canada, while 3.9% were Anglican.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Lutherans made up 3.3% of the population while Baptists constituted 1.9%.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Members of LDS Church are mostly concentrated in the extreme south of the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta has a population of Hutterites, a communal Anabaptist sect similar to the Mennonites, and has a significant population of Seventh-day Adventists.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta is home to several Byzantine Rite Churches as part of the legacy of Eastern European immigration, including the Ukrainian Catholic Eparchy of Edmonton, and the Ukrainian Orthodox Church of Canada's Western Diocese which is based in Edmonton.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Muslims made up 3.2% of the population, Sikhs 1.5%, Buddhists 1.2%, and Hindus 1.0%.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Many of these are immigrants, but others have roots that go back to the first settlers of the prairies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Canada's oldest mosque, the Al-Rashid Mosque, is in Edmonton, whereas Calgary is home to Canada's largest mosque, the Baitun Nur Mosque.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Alberta is also home to a growing Jewish population of about 15,400 people who constituted 0.3% of Alberta's population.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p01] Most of Alberta's Jews live in the metropolitan areas of Calgary (8,200) and Edmonton (5,500).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] While most Albertans work in the service sector, Alberta does possess a significant industrial base, intelligence economy and energy sector.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] This energy sector is famously focused in oil and gas extraction.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Oil and gas has been culturally influential, having shaped politics, generated "striking it rich" narratives, and created boom-and-bust cycles.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The majority of Alberta's exports are sent to the United States, and consist of 70% oil and gas, 13% food products, and 12% industrial products.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Before European contact, Indigenous peoples maintained wide trade networks across Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Then, the fur trade, dominated by the Hudson's Bay Company and the North West Company became the region's first major export economy in the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Following the transfer of Rupert's Land to Canada in 1870, Alberta's economy transitioned to agriculture and ranching.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The completion of the Canadian Pacific Railway in the 1880s facilitated large-scale settlement and grain exports, particularly wheat, establishing agriculture as the province's new economic backbone.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] A major shift came in 1947 with the discovery of oil near Leduc, launching Alberta's rise as Canada's top oil producer.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] While oil brought prosperity, the 1980s, 2008 and 2014 saw economic setbacks due to price crashes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Since then, Alberta has worked to diversify its economy, expanding into technology, renewable energy, tourism, and finance to reduce its dependence on oil.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Agriculture employed 35,900 people in 2021, representing roughly 2% of provincial employment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Out of them, 19,500 were employed in animal production, 11,800 were employed in crop production, 2,000 were employed in mix farming and 2,600 in support activities or agriculture.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The province has over three million head of cattle, and Alberta beef has a healthy worldwide market.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Forty per cent of all Canadian beef is produced in Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The province also produces the most bison meat in Canada.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Sheep for wool and mutton are also raised.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Wheat and canola are primary farm crops, with Alberta leading the provinces in spring wheat production; other grains are also prominent.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Much of the farming is dryland farming, often with fallow seasons interspersed with cultivation.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Continuous cropping (in which there is no fallow season) is gradually becoming a more common mode of production because of increased profits and a reduction of soil erosion.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Across the province, the once common grain elevator is slowly being lost as rail lines are decreasing; farmers typically truck the grain to central points.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2016, forestry provided over 15,000 jobs and generated over $1.0 billion to employment income, $2.6 billion to the provincial GDP, and over $6.1 billion in revenue.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Uses for harvested timber include pulpwood, hardwood, engineered wood and bioproducts such as chemicals and biofuels.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Hybrid canola also requires bee pollination, and some beekeepers service this need.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The mining and quarrying sector, excluding oil and gas, employed approximately 4,300 Albertans in 2021 (around 0.2% of the population) and focused on the mining of coal and mineral resources, such as sand, gravel, salt, limestone, clay, shale and more.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Oil and gas extraction itself however is Alberta's largest and most economically dominant primary industry.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2021, the industry employed roughly 84,500 people in extraction, with another 50,500 in support activities—totaling approximately 135,000 jobs or about 5.6% of Alberta's total employment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In terms of economic output, the sector accounted for approximately 27% of Alberta's GDP in 2022.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta also produced about 4.3 million barrels (680,000 m3) of crude oil per day in 2023, making up 84% of Canada's total oil production.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta is the largest producer of conventional crude oil, synthetic crude, natural gas and gas products in Canada.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta is the world's second-largest exporter of natural gas and the fourth-largest producer.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Two of the largest producers of petrochemicals in North America are in central and north-central Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In both Red Deer and Edmonton, polyethylene and vinyl manufacturers produce products that are shipped all over the world.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Edmonton's oil refineries provide the raw materials for a large petrochemical industry to the east of Edmonton.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The Athabasca oil sands surrounding Fort McMurray have estimated unconventional oil reserves approximately equal to the conventional oil reserves of the rest of the world, estimated to be 1.6 trillion barrels (250 km3).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Many companies employ both conventional strip mining and non-conventional in situ methods to extract the bitumen from the oil sands.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Another factor determining the viability of oil extraction from the oil sands is the price of oil.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The oil price increases since 2003 have made it profitable to extract this oil, which in the past would give little profit or even a loss.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] By mid-2014, rising costs and stabilizing oil prices threatened the economic viability of some projects.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] An example of this was the shelving of the Joslyn North project in the Athabasca region in May 2014.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] With concerted effort and support from the provincial government, several high-tech industries have found their birth in Alberta, notably patents related to interactive liquid-crystal display systems.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] While not as important as its service sector or as influential as its oil and gas industry, Alberta's secondary sector — comprising manufacturing, construction, and utilities — is still of importance, especially to employment and economic diversification.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2021, Alberta's manufacturing sector employed approximately 122,300 individuals, accounting for 5% of the province's total employment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The sector also contributed $23.4 billion, or 8%, to Alberta's Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Key subsectors include food manufacturing (15.8% of manufacturing employment), fabricated metal products (13.6%), machinery (9.8%), wood products (9.8%), and chemicals (8.7%).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Notably, 96% of these jobs were full-time, and 73% of the workforce fell within the core working age of 25–54.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] However, with 20% of workers aged 55 and older, the sector faces impending retirements that could lead to significant job vacancies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta's construction industry is a major employer, with 222,200 individuals working in the sector in 2021, representing 10% of the province's workforce.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The industry contributed $23.6 billion to Alberta's GDP, equating to 8% of the total.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Employment is distributed across trade contracting (54.8%), building construction (30.8%), and heavy and civil engineering construction (14.4%).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The workforce is predominantly male (84%), with a significant portion (27%) being self-employed.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Additionally, Indigenous workers constitute 13.5% of the construction labor force, surpassing their representation in the overall provincial workforce.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The utilities sector, which encompasses electricity generation, transmission, and distribution, employed 13,354 Albertans in 2022.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Employment here grew at an average annual rate of 2.6% between 2017 and 2022, largely because of the expansion of renewable energy sources.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta's service sector employs around 80% of Albertans, in various fields like retail, healthcare, education, professional services, tourism, FIRE (finance, investment and real estate), transportation and warehousing, food services, public administration, arts and recreation, and more.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Therefore, it unsurprisingly accounts for the majority of Alberta's economic activity.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The retail and wholesale trade sector is a significant employer in Alberta, accounting for approximately 15% of total provincial employment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2022, wholesale trade contributed $14.7 billion, and retail trade contributed $14.1 billion to Alberta's GDP, collectively making up about 8% of the province's total GDP.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Healthcare and social assistance, which includes hospitals, clinics, nursing homes and community health programs, is similarly one of the largest employers in Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2020, approximately 247,100 individuals were employed in this sector, representing about 11% of the province's total employment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] About 88,800 of these jobs are in the ambulatory health care services sub-sector, while 107,800 are employed in the hospitals sub-sector and 50,500 are employed in nursing and residential care facilities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In terms of economic contribution, the sector added $16.7 billion to Alberta's GDP in 2020, accounting for 5.4% of the provincial total.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Employment prospects here are good, due to an aging population and ongoing labor shortages, particularly in nursing and residential care facilities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Educational services account for 7.1% of total provincial employment in Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2022, of the 168,100 people employed here, about 98,400 people (58.5%) worked in primary and secondary education, 36,400 people (21.7%) worked in university education, 17,800 (10.6%) worked in other schools and educational support, and 12,200 (7.3%) worked in post-secondary education.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2022, the sector contributed $12.4 billion, or 4%, to the provincial GDP.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The finance, insurance, real estate and leasing (or FIRE) is a big part of Alberta's economy.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2023, the finance and insurance sector alone contributed $14.88 billion to the province's GDP, with a five-year average growth rate of 2.8%.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In February 2025, activity in this sub-sector declined for the third consecutive month, reflecting a cooling in home resale activity across the country.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The professional, scientific, and technical services sector has experienced rapid growth in recent times, with employment increasing by 28,700 jobs (15.1%) between 2021 and 2022.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Since 2018, employment has grown by 47,300 jobs (27.6%), making it one of the fastest-growing sectors in Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The transportation and warehousing sector employed 130,900 people in 2021, accounting for 6% of total provincial employment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Employment in this sector increased by 10,600 jobs (8.8%) from 2020 to 2021.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2022, approximately 108,200 people were employed in Alberta's public administration sector, accounting for 4.6% of provincial employment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Employment in this sector increased by 5,000 jobs (4.8%) from 2021 to 2022.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The arts, entertainment, and recreation sector contributed $1.61 billion to Alberta's GDP in 2023, with an 8.2% growth.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] However, over a five-year period, the sector experienced an annualized -3.7% GDP and -3.5% employment decline, despite employing 22,663 people in 2023.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] This may be due to COVID-19 pandemic-related disruptions, but lower funding from government, higher difficulty in obtaining and retaining staff, and shifts in consumer behaviour could also be contributing factors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The accommodation and food services -which encompasses accommodations, food and beverage services, recreation and entertainment, and travel services- is a significant component of Alberta's service economy.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] 140,400 people were employed here in 2023, which accounts for 6.1% of Alberta's total employment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Furthermore, in 2023, the sector contributed approximately $8.1 billion to Alberta's GDP, marking a 7.8% increase from the previous year.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] This growth indicates a strong recovery from the pandemic's impact, with the sector surpassing pre-pandemic levels for the first time.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] According to Alberta Economic Development, Calgary and Edmonton both host over four million visitors annually.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Banff, Jasper and the Rocky Mountains are visited by about three million people per year.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta tourism relies heavily on Southern Ontario tourists, as well as tourists from other parts of Canada, the United States, and many other countries.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] There are also natural attractions like Elk Island National Park, Wood Buffalo National Park, and the Columbia Icefield.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta's Rockies include well-known tourist destinations Banff National Park and Jasper National Park.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The two mountain parks are connected by the scenic Icefields Parkway.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Banff is located 128 km (80 mi) west of Calgary on Highway 1, and Jasper is located 366 km (227 mi) west of Edmonton on the Yellowhead Highway.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Five of Canada's fourteen UNESCO World Heritage Sites are located within the province: Canadian Rocky Mountain Parks, Waterton-Glacier International Peace Park, Wood Buffalo National Park, Dinosaur Provincial Park and Head-Smashed-In Buffalo Jump.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] A number of these areas hold ski resorts, most notably Banff Sunshine, Lake Louise, Marmot Basin, Norquay and Nakiska.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] About 1.2 million people visit the Calgary Stampede, a celebration of Canada's own Wild West and the cattle ranching industry.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] About 700,000 people enjoy Edmonton's K-Days (formerly Klondike Days and Capital EX).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Edmonton was the gateway to the only all-Canadian route to the Yukon gold fields, and the only route which did not require gold-seekers to travel the exhausting and dangerous Chilkoot Pass.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Another tourist destination that draws more than 650,000 visitors each year is the Drumheller Valley, located northeast of Calgary.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Drumheller, known as the "Dinosaur Capital of The World", offers the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Drumheller also had a rich mining history being one of Western Canada's largest coal producers during the war years.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Another attraction in east-central Alberta is Alberta Prairie Railway Excursions, a popular tourist attraction operated out of Stettler, that offers train excursions into the prairie and caters to tens of thousands of visitors every year.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The Government of Alberta is organized as a parliamentary democracy with a unicameral legislature.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Its unicameral legislature—the Legislative Assembly—consists of 87 members elected first past the post (FPTP) from single-member constituencies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Locally municipal governments and school boards are elected and operate separately.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Their boundaries do not necessarily coincide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] As King of Canada, Charles III is the head of state of Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] His duties concerning the Government of Alberta are carried out by Lieutenant Governor Salma Lakhani.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The King and lieutenant governor are figureheads whose actions are highly restricted by custom and constitutional convention.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The lieutenant governor handles numerous honorific duties in the name of the King.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The government is headed by the premier.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The premier is normally a member of the Legislative Assembly, and draws all the members of the Cabinet from among the members of the Legislative Assembly.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The City of Edmonton is the seat of the provincial government—the capital of Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The current premier is Danielle Smith, who was sworn in on October 11, 2022.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta's elections have tended to yield much more conservative outcomes than those of other Canadian provinces.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] From the 1980s to the 2010s, Alberta had three main political parties, the Progressive Conservatives ("Conservatives" or "Tories"), the Liberals, and the social democratic New Democrats.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The strongly conservative Social Credit Party was a power in Alberta for many decades, but fell from the political map after the Progressive Conservatives came to power in 1971.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] For 44 years the Progressive Conservatives governed Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] All types of municipalities are governed by local residents and were incorporated under various provincial acts, with the exception of improvement districts (governed by either the provincial or federal government), and Indian reserves (governed by local band governments under federal jurisdiction).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Policing in the province of Alberta upon its creation was the responsibility of the Royal Northwest Mounted Police.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 1917, due to pressures of the First World War, the Alberta Provincial Police was created.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] This organization policed the province until it was disbanded as a Great Depression-era cost-cutting measure in 1932.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] It was at that time the, now renamed, Royal Canadian Mounted Police resumed policing of the province, specifically RCMP "K" Division.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] With the advent of the Alberta Sheriffs Branch, the distribution of duties of law enforcement in Alberta has been evolving as certain aspects, such as traffic enforcement, mobile surveillance and the close protection of the Premier of Alberta have been transferred to the Sheriffs.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2006, Alberta formed the Alberta Law Enforcement Response Teams (ALERT) to combat organized crime and the serious offences that accompany it.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] ALERT is made up of members of the RCMP, Sheriffs Branch, and various major municipal police forces in Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Military bases in Alberta include Canadian Forces Base (CFB) Cold Lake, CFB Edmonton, CFB Suffield and CFB Wainwright.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Air force units stationed at CFB Cold Lake have access to the Cold Lake Air Weapons Range.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] CFB Edmonton is the headquarters for the 3rd Canadian Division.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] CFB Suffield hosts British troops and is the largest training facility in Canada.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] According to Alberta's 2009 budget, government revenue in that year came mainly from royalties on non-renewable natural resources (30.4%), personal income taxes (22.3%), corporate and other taxes (19.6%), and grants from the federal government primarily for infrastructure projects (9.8%).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2014, Alberta received $6.1 billion in bitumen royalties.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] With the drop in the price of oil in 2015 it was down to $1.4 billion.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2016, Alberta received "about $837 million in royalty payments from oil sands Royalty Projects".
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] According to the 2018–2021 fiscal plan, the two top sources of revenue in 2016 were personal income tax at $10,763 million and federal transfers of $7,976 million with total resource revenue at $3,097 million.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta is the only province in Canada without a provincial sales tax.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta residents are subject to the federal sales tax, the Goods and Services Tax of 5%.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] From 2001 to 2016, Alberta was the only Canadian province to have a flat tax of 10% of taxable income, which was introduced by Premier, Ralph Klein, as part of the Alberta Tax Advantage, which also included a zero-per cent tax on income below a "generous personal exemption".
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2016, under Premier Rachel Notley, while most Albertans continued to pay the 10% income tax rate, new tax brackets 12%, 14%, and 15% for those with higher incomes ($128,145 annually or more) were introduced.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta's personal income tax system maintained a progressive character by continuing to grant residents personal tax exemptions of $18,451, in addition to a variety of tax deductions for persons with disabilities, students, and the aged.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta's municipalities and school jurisdictions have their own governments who usually work in co-operation with the provincial government.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] By 2018, most Albertans continued to pay the 10% income tax rate.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] According to a March 2015 Statistics Canada report, the median household income in Alberta in 2014 was about $100,000, which is 23% higher than the Canadian national average.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Based on Statistic Canada reports, low-income Albertans, who earn less than $25,000 and those in the high-income bracket earning $150,000 or more, are the lowest-taxed people in Canada.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Those in the middle income brackets representing those that earn about $25,000 to $75,000 pay more in provincial taxes than residents in British Columbia and Ontario.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In terms of income tax, Alberta is the "best province" for those with a low income because there is no provincial income tax for those who earn $18,915 or less.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Even with the 2016 progressive tax brackets up to 15%, Albertans who have the highest incomes, those with a $150,000 annual income or more—about 178,000 people in 2015, pay the least in taxes in Canada. — About 1.9 million Albertans earned between $25,000 and $150,000 in 2015.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta also privatized alcohol distribution.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] By 2010, privatization had increased outlets from 304 stores to 1,726; 1,300 jobs to 4,000 jobs; and 3,325 products to 16,495 products.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Tax revenue also increased from $400 million to $700 million.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2017/18 Alberta collected about $2.4 billion in education property taxes from municipalities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta municipalities raise a significant portion of their income through levying property taxes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The value of assessed property in Alberta was approximately $727 billion in 2011.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Most real property is assessed according to its market value.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The exceptions to market value assessment are farmland, railways, machinery and equipment and linear property, all of which is assessed by regulated rates.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Depending on the property type, property owners may appeal a property assessment to their municipal 'Local Assessment Review Board', 'Composite Assessment Review Board,' or the Alberta Municipal Government Board.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Calgary is famous for its Stampede, dubbed "The Greatest Outdoor Show on Earth".
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The Stampede is Canada's biggest rodeo festival and features various races and competitions, such as calf roping and bull riding.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In line with the western tradition of rodeo are the cultural artisans that reside and create unique Alberta western heritage crafts.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Summer brings many festivals to Alberta, especially in Edmonton.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The Edmonton Fringe Festival is the world's second-largest after the Edinburgh Festival.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Both Calgary and Edmonton host many annual festivals and events, including folk music festivals.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The city's "heritage days" festival sees the participation of over 70 ethnic groups.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Edmonton's Churchill Square is home to a large number of the festivals, including A Taste of Edmonton and The Works Art & Design Festival throughout the summer months.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The award comes with $60,000 funding which includes travel and materials costs.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] On January 31, 2019, Lauren Crazybull was named Alberta's first artist in residence.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta is the first province to launch an artist in residence program in Canada.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] As with any Canadian province, the Alberta Legislature has (almost) exclusive authority to make laws respecting education.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] There are forty-two public school jurisdictions in Alberta, and seventeen operating separate school jurisdictions.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Sixteen of the operating separate school jurisdictions have a Catholic electorate, and one (St.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In addition, one Protestant separate school district, Glen Avon, survives as a ward of the St.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The City of Lloydminster straddles the Albertan/Saskatchewan border, and both the public and separate school systems in that city are counted in the above numbers: both of them operate according to Saskatchewan law.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] For many years, the provincial government has funded the greater part of the cost of providing K–12 education.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Prior to 1994, public and separate school boards in Alberta had the legislative authority to levy a local tax on property as supplementary support for local education.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 1994, the government of the province eliminated this right for public school boards, but not for separate school boards.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Since 1994, there has continued to be a tax on property in support of K–12 education; the difference is that the provincial government now sets the mill rate, the money is collected by the local municipal authority and remitted to the provincial government.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The relevant legislation requires that all the money raised by this property tax must go to support K–12 education provided by school boards.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The provincial government pools the property tax funds from across the province and distributes them, according to a formula, to public and separate school jurisdictions and Francophone authorities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Public and separate school boards, charter schools, and private schools all follow the Program of Studies and the curriculum approved by the provincial department of education (Alberta Education).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Homeschool tutors may choose to follow the Program of Studies or develop their own Program of Studies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Several publicly funded post-secondary institutions are governed under the province's *Post-secondary Learning Act*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Nine comprehensive community colleges offer primarily offer diploma and certificate programs, Bow Valley College, Keyano College, Lakeland College, Lethbridge College, Medicine Hat College, NorQuest College, Northern Lakes College, Olds College, and Portage College.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In addition, there are also four polytechnic institutes that provide specific career training and provides apprenticeships and diplomas, the Northern Alberta Institute of Technology, the Southern Alberta Institute of Technology, Northwestern Polytechnic, and Red Deer Polytechnic.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The Banff Centre for Arts and Creativity is a specialized arts and cultural institution that is also empowered to provide diploma programs under the *Post-secondary Learning Act*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta is also home to five independent postsecondary institutions that provide diplomas/degrees for approved programming, Ambrose University, Burman University, Concordia University of Edmonton, The King's University, and St.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Although the five institutions operate under their own legislation, they remain partly governed by the province's *Post-secondary Learning Act*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In addition to these institutions, there are also 190 private career colleges in Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta provides a publicly funded, fully integrated health system, through Alberta Health Services (AHS)—a quasi-independent agency that delivers health care on behalf of the Government of Alberta's Ministry of Health.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The Alberta government provides health services for all its residents as set out by the provisions of the *Canada Health Act* of 1984.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta became Canada's second province (after Saskatchewan) to adopt a Tommy Douglas-style program in 1950, a precursor to the modern medicare system.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta's health care budget was $22.5 billion during the 2018–2019 fiscal year (approximately 45% of all government spending), making it the best-funded health-care system per-capita in Canada.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Every hour the province spends more than $2.5 million, (or $60 million per day), to maintain and improve health care in the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The Edmonton Clinic complex, completed in 2012, provides a similar research, education, and care environment as the Mayo Clinic in the United States.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] All public health care services funded by the Government of Alberta are delivered operationally by Alberta Health Services.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] AHS is the province's single health authority, established on July 1, 2008, which replaced nine regional health authorities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] AHS also funds all ground ambulance services in the province, as well as the province-wide Shock Trauma Air Rescue Service (STARS) air ambulance service.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta is well-connected by air, with international airports in both Calgary and Edmonton.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Calgary International Airport and Edmonton International Airport are the fourth- and fifth-busiest in Canada, respectively.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Edmonton's airport acts as a hub for the Canadian north and has connections to all major Canadian airports as well as airports in the United States, Europe, Mexico, and the Caribbean .
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Calgary, Edmonton, Red Deer, Medicine Hat, and Lethbridge have substantial public transit systems.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In addition to buses, Calgary and Edmonton operate light rail transit (LRT) systems.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Edmonton LRT, which is underground in the downtown core and on the surface outside the downtown core was the first of the modern generation of light rail systems to be built in North America, while the Calgary CTrain has one of the highest numbers of daily riders of any LRT system in North America.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] There are more than 9,000 km (5,600 mi) of operating mainline railway in Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The vast majority of this trackage is owned by the Canadian Pacific Kansas City (CPKC) and Canadian National Railway (CN) companies, which operate freight transport across the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Additional railfreight service in the province is provided by two shortline railways: the Battle River Railway and Forty Mile Rail.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Passenger trains include Via Rail's *Canadian* (Toronto–Vancouver) and Jasper–Prince Rupert trains, which use the CN mainline and pass through Jasper National Park and parallel the Yellowhead Highway during at least part of their routes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The Rocky Mountaineer operates two sections: one from Vancouver to Banff over CP tracks, and a section that travels over CN tracks to Jasper.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] In 2024 Alberta's premier, Danielle Smith, announced a 15-year master plan to expand passenger rail in Alberta.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] This plan envisions rail services to Lethbridge, Medicine Hat, Banff, Grande Prairie, Fort McMurray, and most importantly an intercity rail service between Edmonton and Calgary, as well as commuter rail systems in the respective cities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Ground-breaking was planned for 2027, according to Transportation Minister Devin Dreeshen.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta has over 473,000 km (294,000 mi) of highways and roads in its road network.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The main north–south corridor is Highway 2, which begins south of Cardston at the Carway border crossing and is part of the CANAMEX Corridor.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Beginning at the Coutts border crossing and ending at Lethbridge, Highway 4, effectively extends Interstate 15 into Alberta and is the busiest United States gateway to the province.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Highway 3 joins Lethbridge to Fort Macleod and links Highway 2 to Highway 4.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Highway 2 travels north through Fort Macleod, Calgary, Red Deer, and Edmonton.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] North of Edmonton, the highway continues to Athabasca, then northwesterly along the south shore of Lesser Slave Lake into High Prairie, north to Peace River, west to Fairview and finally south to Grande Prairie, where it ends at an interchange with Highway 43.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The section of Highway 2 between Calgary and Edmonton has been named the Queen Elizabeth II Highway to commemorate the visit of the monarch in 2005.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Highway 2 is supplemented by two more highways that run parallel to it: Highway 22, west of Highway 2, known as *Cowboy Trail*, and Highway 21, east of Highway 2.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Highway 43 travels northwest into Grande Prairie and the Peace River Country.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Travelling northeast from Edmonton, the Highway 63 connects to Fort McMurray and the Athabasca oil sands.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Alberta has two main east–west corridors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The southern corridor, part of the Trans-Canada Highway system, enters the province near Medicine Hat, runs westward through Calgary, and leaves Alberta through Banff National Park.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The northern corridor, also part of the Trans-Canada network and known as the Yellowhead Highway (Highway 16), runs west from Lloydminster in eastern Alberta, through Edmonton and Jasper National Park into British Columbia.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] One of the most scenic drives is along the Icefields Parkway, which runs for 228 km (142 mi) between Jasper and Lake Louise, with mountain ranges and glaciers on either side of its entire length.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] A third corridor stretches across southern Alberta; Highway 3 runs between Crowsnest Pass and Medicine Hat through Lethbridge and forms the eastern portion of the Crowsnest Highway.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Another major corridor through central Alberta is Highway 11 (also known as the David Thompson Highway), which runs east from the Saskatchewan River Crossing in Banff National Park through Rocky Mountain House and Red Deer, connecting with Highway 12, 20 km (12 mi) west of Stettler.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] The highway connects many of the smaller towns in central Alberta with Calgary and Edmonton, as it crosses Highway 2 just west of Red Deer.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Urban stretches of Alberta's major highways and freeways are often called *trails*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] For example, Highway 2, the main north–south highway in the province, is called Deerfoot Trail as it passes through Calgary but becomes Calgary Trail (southbound) and Gateway Boulevard (northbound) as it enters Edmonton and then turns into St.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Albert Trail as it leaves Edmonton for the City of St.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/alberta-canada-p02] Calgary, in particular, has a tradition of calling its largest urban expressways *trails* and naming many of them after prominent First Nations individuals and tribes, such as Crowchild Trail, Deerfoot Trail, and Stoney Trail.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Today there are numerous types of automatic fire suppression systems and standards for each one.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Systems are as diverse as the many applications.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] In general, however, automatic fire suppression systems fall into two categories: *engineered* and *pre-engineered* systems.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] By definition, an automatic fire suppression system can operate without human intervention.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] To do so it must possess a means of detection, actuation and delivery.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] In many systems, detection is accomplished by mechanical or electrical means.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Mechanical detection uses fusible-link or thermo-bulb detectors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] These detectors are designed to separate at a specific temperature and release tension on a release mechanism.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Electrical detection uses heat detectors equipped with self-restoring, normally-open contacts which close when a predetermined temperature is reached.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Remote and local manual operation is also possible.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Actuation usually involves either a pressurized fluid and a release valve, or in some cases an electric pump.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Delivery is accomplished by means of piping and nozzles.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Nozzle design is specific to the agent used and coverage desired.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Water is the most prevalent fire suppression agent in use worldwide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] However, the use of water does have some limitations, which can range from inadequate supplies (particularly in less developed regions) to operations and processes which are highly susceptible to water damage.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] In some cases, certain contents or processes (such as water-reactive chemicals or metals, molten materials, etc.) are truly incompatible with water; water discharge could lead to explosion.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Despite their effectiveness, chemical fire extinguishing agents are not without disadvantages.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] In the early 20th century, carbon tetrachloride was extensively used as a dry cleaning solvent, a refrigerant and as a fire extinguishing agent.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] In time, it was found carbon tetrachloride could lead to severe health effects.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] From the mid-1960s Halon 1301 was the industry standard for protecting high-value assets from the threat of fire.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301 had many benefits as a fire suppression agent; it is fast-acting, safe for assets and required minimal storage space.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301's major drawbacks are that it depletes atmospheric ozone and is potentially harmful to humans.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Since 1987, some 191 nations have signed The Montreal Protocol on Substances That Deplete the Ozone Layer.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] The Protocol is an international treaty designed to protect the ozone layer by phasing out the production of a number of substances believed to be responsible for ozone depletion.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Among these were halogenated hydrocarbons often used in fire suppression.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] As a result, manufacturers have focused on alternatives to Halon 1301 and Halon 1211 (halogenated hydrocarbons).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] A number of countries have also taken steps to mandate the removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Most notably these include Germany and Australia, the first two countries in the world to require this action.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] In both of these countries complete removal of installed Halon systems has been completed except for a very few essential-use applications.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] The European Union is currently undergoing a similar mandated removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire extinguisher patent was issued to Alanson Crane of Virginia on Feb.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire sprinkler system was patented by H.W.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] But the first practical automatic sprinkler system was invented in 1874 by Henry S.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] He installed the system in a piano factory he owned.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Since the early 1990s manufacturers have successfully developed safe and effective Halon alternatives.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] These include DuPont's FM-200, American Pacific's Halotron, FirePro's FPC Compound, Plumis’ Automist and 3M's Novec 1230 Fire Protection Fluid.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Generally, the Halon replacement agents available today fall into two broad categories, in-kind (gaseous extinguishing agents) or not in-kind (alternative technologies).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] In-kind gaseous agents generally fall into two further categories, halocarbons and inert gases.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/automatic-fire-suppression] Not in-kind alternatives include such options as water mist or the use of early warning smoke detection systems.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] A **carbon monoxide detector** or **CO detector** is a device which detects the presence of carbon monoxide (CO) gas, and is used to prevent carbon monoxide poisoning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Most CO detectors use a sensor with a defined, limited lifespan, and will not work indefinitely.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] In the late 1990s, Underwriters Laboratories (UL) changed the definition of a single station CO detector with a sound device to **carbon monoxide (CO) alarm**.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] This applies to all CO safety alarms that meet the UL 2034 standard; however for passive indicators and system devices that meet UL 2075, UL refers to these as *carbon monoxide detectors*.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] CO is a colorless, tasteless, and odorless gas produced by incomplete combustion of carbon-containing materials.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] It is often referred to as the "silent killer" because it is virtually undetectable by humans.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] In a study by UL, "Sixty percent of Americans could not identify any potential signs of a CO leak in the home".
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Elevated levels of CO can be dangerous to humans depending on the amount present and length of exposure.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Smaller concentrations can be harmful over longer periods while increasing concentrations require diminishing exposure times to be harmful.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] CO detectors are designed to measure CO levels over time and sound an alarm before dangerous levels of CO accumulate in an environment, giving people adequate warning to safely ventilate the area or evacuate.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Some system-connected detectors also alert a monitoring service that can dispatch emergency services if necessary.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] While CO detectors do not serve as smoke detectors and vice versa, combined smoke/CO detectors are also sold.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] In the home, some common sources of CO include open flames, space heaters, water heaters, blocked chimneys or running a car or grill inside a garage.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The devices can either be battery-operated or AC-powered (with or without a battery backup).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Battery-powered devices advertise a battery lifetime of up to 10 years.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The gas sensors in a CO alarm have a limited life span, typically two to five years.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Newer models are designed to signal a need to be replaced after a set period.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] CO detectors all have "test" buttons like smoke detectors, but the test buttons only test the battery, electronic circuit, and buzzer, not the alarm's ability to sense gas.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] People living in all-electric homes do not need CO detectors unless there is an attached garage with a non-electric car, or if a backup generator is used too close to the living quarters.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] CO detectors are available as stand-alone models, or system-connected devices which can be monitored remotely.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The primary purpose of CO detectors is to sound an alarm to warn occupants of an enclosed space of a dangerous level of carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The alarm should sound within 60 minutes if the concentration rises to 70 PPM, within 10 minutes at 150 PPM, in 4 minutes at 400 PPM, and immediately at 500 PPM or greater.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The alarm should not sound too quickly, as brief false alarms may prompt users to disable the alarm, leaving them unprotected.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Some alarm devices may display the CO level.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] There are also measuring instruments designed to display CO concentrations down to low, non-dangerous levels, rather than detect and warn of dangerous levels.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Some detectors without UL certification have been found not to sound at the specified threshold, or to sound within seconds.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Several carbon monoxide detection methods are used and documented in industry specifications published by UL.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Early designs used a chemical detector consisting of a white pad that faded to a brownish or blackish color in the presence of carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Such detectors were inexpensive but only give a visual warning.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] As carbon monoxide-related deaths increased during the 1990s, audible alarms became standard.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The alarm points on carbon monoxide detectors are not a simple alarm level (as in smoke detectors) but are a concentration-time function.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] 100 parts per million (PPM)) the detector does not sound an alarm for many tens of minutes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] At 400 PPM, the alarm sounds within a few minutes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] This concentration-time function is intended to mimic the uptake of carbon monoxide in the body while also preventing false alarms due to brief bursts of carbon monoxide from relatively common sources such as cigarette smoke.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Four types of sensors are available, varying in cost, accuracy, and speed of response.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Most detectors do not have replaceable sensors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The detector consists of a pad of a colored chemical which changes color upon reaction with carbon monoxide.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] They only provide a qualitative warning of the gas, however.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The main advantage of these detectors is their low cost; the downside that they offer the lowest level of protection.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] As the reaction progresses, the release of palladium causes the color to change from yellow to brown to black.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] A biomimetic sensor works in a fashion similar to hemoglobin which darkens in the presence of CO proportional to the amount of carbon monoxide in the surrounding environment.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] It uses cyclodextrins, a chromophore, and a number of metal salts.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] This can either be seen directly or connected to an infrared source of photons such as an IR LED and then monitored using a photodiode.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Battery lifespan is usually two to three years with conventional alkaline, but a lithium battery will last the life of the product.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The biotechnology-based sensors have a useful operational life of six years.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] These products were the first to enter the mass market, but because they cost more than other sensors they are mostly used in higher-end areas and RVs.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The technology has been improved and is the most reliable technology, according to a report from Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Electrochemical Carbon Monoxide sensors.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Both sensors and alarms are from different companies.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The electrochemical detector uses the principle of a fuel cell to generate an electrical current when the gas to be detected undergoes a chemical reaction.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The generated current is precisely related to the amount of carbon monoxide in the immediate environment close to the sensor.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Essentially, the electrochemical cell consists of a container, two electrodes, connection wires, and an electrolyte, typically sulfuric acid.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Carbon monoxide is oxidized at one electrode to carbon dioxide while oxygen is consumed at the other electrode.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Test buttons only indicate the operational effectiveness of the battery, circuit, and buzzer.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The only way to fully test the operation of a CO alarm using an electrochemical cell is with a known source of calibrated test gas delivered in a shroud to maintain the concentration level for the test period.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Thin wires of the semiconductor tin dioxide on an insulating ceramic base provide a sensor monitored by an integrated circuit.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] This sensing element must be heated to approximately 400 °C for operation.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Oxygen increases the resistance of the tin dioxide while carbon monoxide reduces it.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The integrated circuit monitors the resistance of the sensing element.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Lifespans are approximately five years and alarms need testing on installation and at least annually with a test gas.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Due to the large power demand of this sensor, it is usually powered from the mains.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] A battery-powered, pulsed sensor is available with a lifetime of months.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] This technology is widely used in Japan and elsewhere in the Far East, with some market penetration in the US.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] However, the superior performance of electrochemical cell technology is beginning to displace this technology.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Although all home detectors use an audible alarm signal as the primary indicator, some versions also offer a digital readout of the CO concentration, in parts per million (PPM).
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Typically, they can display both the current reading and a peak reading from memory of the highest level measured over some time.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] These advanced models cost somewhat more but are otherwise similar to the basic models.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The models with display have the advantages of indicating levels below the alarm threshold, reporting levels that may have occurred during an absence, and assessing the degree of hazard if the alarm sounds.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] They may also aid emergency responders in evaluating the level of past or ongoing exposure or danger.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Portable detectors are designed for aircraft, cars and trucks.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] They warn vehicle occupants of any CO hazard.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Portable meters which display CO concentration down to a few PPM are more sensitive than home safety CO detectors and correspondingly much more expensive.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] They are used by industrial hygienists and first responders, and for maintenance and tracing a CO leak.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] These devices measure low levels of CO in seconds, rather than minutes or hours like residential alarms.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Like other test equipment, professional CO meters must be tested and recalibrated periodically.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] CO alarm requirements came into effect on October 15, 2014 in Ontario, and there is a strong movement in Alberta to make CO detectors mandatory in all homes.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] In the US (as of January 2017) 32 states have enacted statutes regarding carbon monoxide detectors, and another 11 have promulgated regulations on CO detectors, as well as in Washington DC and New York City.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The Canadian Mortgage and Housing Association reports, "The standards organizations of Canada (CSA) and the United States (UL) have coordinated the writing of CO standards and product testing.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The standards as of 2010 prohibit showing CO levels of less than 30 PPM on digital displays.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The most recent standards also require the alarm to sound at higher levels of CO than with previous editions of the standard.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] The reasoning behind these changes is to reduce calls to fire stations, utilities and emergency response teams when the levels of CO are not life threatening.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] This change will also reduce the number of calls to these agencies due to detector inaccuracy or the presence of other gases.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Consequently, new alarms will not sound at CO concentrations up to 70 PPM.
[src:carbon-monoxide-detector/carbon-monoxide-detector] Note that these concentrations are significantly in excess of the Canadian health guidelines," (and also in excess of US Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) Permissible exposure limits, which is 50 PPM).
